Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

Custodian Accused Of Stealing Museum Artifacts
POSTED: 2:19 pm PDT May 25, 2007

SAN DIEGO -- A former employee of the San Diego Natural History Museum is behind bars Friday after being arrested on suspicion of stealing items worth $15,000, according to San Diego police.

Ruben Lopez, 23, of Kensington was taken into custody Thursday, after detectives served a search warrant at his home.

Officials said they found the missing items as well as methamphetamine and drug paraphernalia inside Lopez's home.

Police said Lopez allegedly stole the items in May of 2004 when he was a custodian at the museum.

Investigators said museum proprietors initially were not certain whether the items had been stolen or misplaced during a reorganization of exhibits.

Among the artifacts recovered was a preserved hawksbill sea turtle.

"There's a lot of damage -- the bill is broken, the legs are dangling," said museum spokeswoman Delle Willett. "It looks like someone had a tug-of-war with it."

Detectives also recovered a Spanish history book dating to 1754 and some antique survey equipment.

"We have a whole new security system in place, and we are also doing background checks," Willett said. "This shouldn't happen again."

Lopez was charged with grand theft, possession of narcotics for sale and embezzlement.

http://www.nbcsandiego.com




