Message: 16
Date: Mon, 28 May 2007 15:28:01 +0200
From: Museum Security Network Mailing list <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Subject: [MSN] US. Felony charge for student in Nobel Prize medal
	theft
To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <465AD8E1.4040403@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

Felony charge for student in Nobel Prize medal theft

OAKLAND ? The University of California, Berkeley, student arrested for stealing the university's first Nobel Prize medal has been charged with felony grand theft and could face up to one year in prison.

Ian Michael Sanchez, 22, who worked at the Lawrence Hall of Science when he was arrested for stealing the medal, was arraigned Friday, a spokeswoman for the Alameda County District's Office said.

He is due back in court on June 8 to enter a plea.

The coin-like 1939 Nobel Prize in physics was awarded to Professor Ernest O. Lawrence for the invention of the cyclotron, an accelerator of sub-atomic particles that led to the nuclear age. The medal was in a locked display case at the Lawrence Hall of Science in the Berkeley hills when it was stolen in late February.

It was recovered a few days later after Sanchez showed the 23-karat gold award, worth $4,200, to friends and one of them reported the theft to authorities, police said.

He was later arrested and released on bail.

The 4-ounce prize had been housed with other artifacts of Lawrence's life and work in the publicly accessible and sprawling E.O. Lawrence Memorial Room at the science museum. Hall of science spokeswoman Linda Schneider said the theft, and now the criminal charge, is disturbing considering the museum is usually a safe and quiet place.

"Everybody was pretty saddened by it and even more so now that it's such a serious charge," Schneider said.

The medal has been moved to a "very secure location" and out of public view, Schneider said.

A replica of the award is on display, she said.

The real medal will be returned to a new display as part of the commemoration of the 40th anniversary of the Lawrence Hall of Science in May 2008, Schneider said.

Schneider added that there "definitely has been discussion about security issues" since the theft.

Schneider said Sanchez, who earned roughly $10 an hour when he worked at the Hall of Science, told authorities he used a key to open the small lock on the medal's display case and snatched the medal "on a whim." Police said the lock was jimmied.

Sanchez may also face student conduct charges ? a warning, suspension or expulsion ? but that was not known Friday.

"Federal student privacy regulations prohibit the university from commenting on anything related to disciplinary actions involving the student," UC spokeswoman Mudle Felde said.

Sanchez was not available for comment late Friday.

Lawrence died in 1958. The Lawrence Hall of Science was named in his honor. One of his cyclotrons, not the first, which was teacup size, is displayed in front of the Hall of Science, a university spokesman said.

Contact staff writer Kristin Bender at kbender@angnewspapers.com.

http://www.insidebayarea.com




